Mammograms work very well at detecting early breast cancer, but they 're not perfect. The milk duct technique, called ductal lavage, is among those experimental alternatives. Ductal lavage signaled cancer in only a fraction of these women, lead researcher Dr. Seema Khan reported Tuesday in the Journal of the National Cancer Institute. The test uncovered clear cancer signs in just 13 percent of the cancerous breasts tested, and possible signs in 42 percent. 